article.headline: Seton Hall 66, Manhattan 52
article.story: EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. (AP) -- Seton Hall was impressive on defense and efficient on offense in winning its season opener. The Pirates' reward? A trip to top-ranked Duke. Kelly Whitney scored 25 points and Jamar Nutter added 17 to lead Seton Hall to a 66-52 victory over Manhattan on Monday night in the opening round of the Preseason NIT. The win advances the Pirates to a second-round game at No. 1 Duke. The Blue Devils beat Boston University 64-47 on Monday. "The way we played this game, I couldn't ask for anything more going to Duke," said Louis Orr, in his fifth season as coach at Seton Hall. "That was a great defensive effort from beginning to end. It was the most focused I've seen a team defensively since I've been here." Whitney, a senior center who led the Pirates in scoring and rebounding last season, and Nutter, a junior guard, combined for all but three of Seton Hall's points in an 11-3 spurt to open the second half. The run gave the Pirates a 41-25 lead. "We're a defensive team and my job is to get them fired up," Whitney said. He was asked what he thought about Wednesday night at Cameron Indoor Stadium. "A war," he said. "It will be just like my sophomore year when we played them in the NCAA tournament." The Pirates upset Arizona in the first round that year but lost 90-62 to the Blue Devils, who fell one game shy of the Final Four. "I'm glad I'm taking this team down there," Orr said. "Character means a lot." A drive by Stan Gaines, a junior transfer from Minnesota, gave Seton Hall its biggest lead, 50-32, with 8:31 to play. The Jaspers (0-1) scored the next 10 points to get within eight with 5:55 to go, but Whitney and Nutter both scored down low in a 6-2 run that made it 56-44 with 4:21 left. Gaines had 13 points for the Pirates. Sophomore forward C.J. Anderson had 16 points for Manhattan, but he was 5-for-20 from the field as he tried time and again to go inside against the bigger and deeper Pirates. Manhattan finished 17-for-65 from the field (26.2 percent), including 7-for-24 from 3-point range. The Jaspers also struggled at the free throw line, going 11-for-21. "It's a big challenge to play a Big East team on the road this early in the season," Manhattan coach Bobby Gonzalez said. "We had no answer for their strength and size. We missed 10 free throws. You won't win on the road with numbers like those." Seton Hall shot 43.5 percent for the game (20-for-46) with most of the shots coming down low. The Pirates were 3-for-8 on 3s with Gaines going 2-for-3. Anderson couldn't say enough about Whitney. "He had too many moves and finished around the basket," Anderson said. "He affected the shot every time you went to shoot." Seton Hall led 30-22 after a first half that looked like the first of the season for both teams. The shooting percentages of the two teams added together just reached 60 percent. Whitney became the 33rd player in Seton Hall history to reach the 1,000-point mark. He has 1,018. His career high is 27 points, against Saint Peter's, another Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference school, last season. Whitney said the short preparation for Duke won't be different than it was getting ready for Manhattan. "All we can do is be prepared and focused and carry out our task," he said.
